{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513864","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513864"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:26+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:15:26+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12240"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12240","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12240"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.15,0.07,0.36,0.35]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4762"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101627"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4762","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4762"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12240"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84068"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"1058"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"1142"},{"type":"tags","id":"3496"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7566"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8189"},{"type":"contributions","id":"8225"},{"type":"contributions","id":"12937"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15155"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15207"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34266"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35222"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36015"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42719"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43306"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101627","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/101627"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 18-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with a two-hour history of intense pruritus and raised wheals on his arms and chest. He has a history of peanut allergy diagnosed in childhood and has avoided peanut-containing foods since then. He takes no regular medications.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears uncomfortable. His pulse rate is 132/min, blood pressure 98/60 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 96% on room air, and temperature 36.8\u00b0C. There are several raised wheals and annular plaques on his arms and upper torso. Suddenly, the patient becomes short of breath and develops audible wheezing. 500 micrograms of adrenaline is administered via intramuscular injection.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next step in management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Oral corticosteroids","Intubation","Oral antihistamines","Intravenous fluid bolus","High-flow oxygen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms and signs of anaphylaxis, which has progressed from initial urticaria to respiratory distress. Anaphylaxis is a life-threatening systemic allergic reaction characterized by rapid onset of airway, breathing, or circulatory problems, often associated with skin and mucosal changes.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EFollowing the ABCDE approach to managing the acutely unwell patient, after ensuring the airway is patent (A), the next priority is breathing (B). While the patient\u0027s airway appears intact, he is developing respiratory compromise with shortness of breath and wheezing. The \u003Cstrong\u003Ehigh-flow oxygen\u003C/strong\u003E is therefore the most appropriate next step in management. This should be administered at 15 L/min via a non-rebreather mask regardless of oxygen saturations, as per standard anaphylaxis management protocols. Even though the patient\u0027s SpO2 is 96%, high-flow oxygen is essential to support respiratory function during anaphylaxis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAfter addressing airway and breathing, circulation (C) would be the next priority. An \u003Cstrong\u003Eintravenous fluid bolus\u003C/strong\u003E would be important, especially given the patient\u0027s tachycardia and hypotension (BP 98/60 mmHg), suggesting early compensatory shock. However, securing oxygenation takes precedence in the ABCDE sequence. IV fluids would typically follow immediately after oxygen administration.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral corticosteroids\u003C/strong\u003E are part of second-line treatment for anaphylaxis and may help prevent biphasic reactions. However, they have a delayed onset of action (taking hours to work) and do not address the immediate life-threatening aspects of anaphylaxis. They would be administered after the initial resuscitation steps of adrenaline, oxygen, and fluids.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntubation\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered if there was severe airway compromise or if the patient failed to respond to initial management with adrenaline and oxygen. At this point, it is premature to escalate to intubation without first optimising non-invasive respiratory support.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOral antihistamines\u003C/strong\u003E may help with cutaneous symptoms but have no role in treating the life-threatening respiratory and cardiovascular manifestations of anaphylaxis. They are not a priority in acute management and would be considered only after the patient is stabilized.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe complete management of anaphylaxis includes the following steps in order:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Col\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ERemove allergen if still present and call for assistance\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELay person flat (unless breathing is difficult, then allow to sit with legs outstretched)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGive intramuscular adrenaline (already done in this case)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAdminister high-flow oxygen\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EEstablish IV access and give fluid resuscitation\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EContact emergency services if not already in hospital\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EConsider repeat adrenaline dose after 5 minutes if no response\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMonitor vital signs continuously\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECommence CPR if unresponsive and not breathing normally\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EObserve for at least 4-6 hours due to risk of biphasic reactions\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ol\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Anaphylaxis requires immediate treatment with intramuscular adrenaline followed by high-flow oxygen regardless of oxygen saturation.","The ABCDE approach to managing anaphylaxis prioritizes airway, breathing, and circulation with high-flow oxygen being essential for supporting breathing.","Anaphylaxis can initially present as acute urticaria before progressing to respiratory and cardiovascular symptoms."],"references":["ASCIA Guidelines - Acute Management of Anaphylaxis [Online]. In: Australasian Society of Clinical Immunology and Allergy (ASCIA). 2023 [cited 2023 Feb]. Available at: https://www.allergy.org.au/hp/papers/acute-management-of-anaphylaxis-guidelines","Anaphylaxis: emergency management for health professionals. Aust Prescr 2018;41:54. Available at: https://doi.org/10.18773/austprescr.2018.014","Silvestre Salvador JF, Gim\u00e9nez-Arnau AM, G\u00f3mez de la Fuente E, Gonz\u00e1lez Del Castillo J, Mart\u00ednez Virto AM, et al. Managing urticaria in the emergency department: recommendations of a multidisciplinary expert panel. Emergencias. 2021 Aug;33(4):299-308. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/34251143/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84068"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12240"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"84068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/84068"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-03T14:59:27+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-14T16:16:06+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4762"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"101627"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id"